\begin_layout Section
Master Equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The density matrix master equation is basic to quantum theory.
 It has a memory requirement that scales as 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{2\lambda M}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 modes, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\ln(N_{max})$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{max}$
\end_inset

 is the dimension of the Hilbert space of a single mode.
 This becomes exponentially difficult to solve numerically as 
\begin_inset Formula $M\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The master equation treated here and elsewhere is repeated for reference
 purposes.
 It has the standard Lindblad form that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\dot{\rho} & =\mathcal{L}\rho\label{eq:Lindblad_Master_Equation}\\
 & =-i\left[\hat{H},\rho\right]+\sum_{j}\gamma_{j}\left(2\hat{L}_{j}\rho\hat{L}_{j}^{\dagger}-\hat{L}_{j}^{\dagger}\hat{L}_{j}\rho-\rho\hat{L}_{j}^{\dagger}\hat{L}_{j}\right)
\end{align}

\end_inset

Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is the reversible system Hamiltonian, 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{j}$
\end_inset

 are operators that couple the quantum system to the dissipative reservoir,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{j}$
\end_inset

 is the decay rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Provide that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is normalized, the expectation values of observables 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{O}$
\end_inset

 are given by: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle \hat{O}\right\rangle =Tr\left(\rho\hat{O}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The definitions used here mean that for the case of linear damping with
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}=\hat{a}$
\end_inset

, the rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is the amplitude decay rate.
 This abstract notation does not include the effects of finite temperatures,
 which are explained below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The rate is written explicitly here.
 This is useful for xSPDE inputs, which use standard dimensionless operators.
 Some references combine the rate with the operator 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gisin1992quantum"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=1.$
\end_inset

 Others use a rate constant of 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa=2\gamma$
\end_inset

, i.e., the number decay rate.
 Some combine 
\emph on
this
\emph default
 rate with the operator, defining 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{c}_{j}=\sqrt{2\gamma_{j}}\hat{L}_{j}$
\end_inset

., giving a fourth type of damping operator convention.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Including finite temperature reservoir occupation numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{n}_{j}$
\end_inset

 explicitly, the quantum master equation with damping rates 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{j}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
{\frac{\partial\hat{\rho}}{\partial t}} & =-i\left[\hat{H},\hat{\rho}\right]+\sum_{j}\Gamma_{j}\left(\bar{n}_{j}+1\right)(2\hat{A}_{j}\hat{\rho}\hat{A}_{j}^{\dagger}-\hat{A}_{j}^{\dagger}\hat{A}_{j}\hat{\rho}-\hat{\rho}\hat{A}_{j}^{\dagger}\hat{A}_{j})\,\,\nonumber \\
 & +\sum_{j}\Gamma_{j}\bar{n}_{j}(2\hat{A}_{j}^{\dagger}\hat{\rho}\hat{A}_{j}-\hat{A}_{j}\hat{A}_{j}^{\dagger}\hat{\rho}-\hat{\rho}\hat{A}_{j}\hat{A}_{j}^{\dagger})\,\,,\label{eq:master-equation-1}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{j}$
\end_inset

