\begin_layout Section
Stochastic Schrödinger equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A stochastic Schrödinger equation (SSE) is an equation with noise terms
 used to solve a dissipative master equation by random sampling, and was
 originally developed for applications in quantum foundations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "pearle1979toward,Ghirardi1986PhysRevD.34.470,gisin1992quantum"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 It has the advantage over a master equation that for large numbers of modes
 it uses less storage.
 This requires 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{\lambda M}$
\end_inset

complex numbers for the  storage of an 
\begin_inset Formula $M-$
\end_inset

mode quantum system, compared to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim e^{2\lambda M}$
\end_inset

 for the master equation, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\log_{e}(N)$
\end_inset

 for an 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

-level local Hilbert space.
 This is exponentially large, but the memory required is less than with
 a density matrix equation, doubling the number of modes that are accessible.
 The drawback is that many parallel trajectories must be averaged in order
 to give a low final sampling error.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An SSE can also be regarded in certain cases as providing a direct simulation
 of the measurement process, which means that the information recorded in
 a simulation is similar to the information measured in a quantum experiment.
 This requires a suitable choice of the method, sometimes called an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

unraveling
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and the stochastic integration algorithm.
 Different unravellings mean different measurements and different convergence
 rates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are many versions of the SSE, which use different normalization, different
 random noises or different types of stochastic calculus.
 Noises can be real or complex, and either continuous or with discrete jumps.
 These are different 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

unravellings
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, and correspond physically to distinct measurement devices and outcomes.
 They also have different sampling errors.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Compared to phase-space expansions, the SSE method has the problem that
 storage requirements are exponential in the system size, although it may
 have lower sampling errors for high nonlinearities.
 This limits mode numbers to 
\begin_inset Formula $10-50$
\end_inset

, depending on the size of the Hilbert space per mode and the computational
 resources.
 The approach is most useful for small mode numbers, especially for large
 nonlinearities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Normalized Ito SSE
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A widely used form of the continuous noise, normalized SSE is as follows
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gisin1992quantum"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, in the Ito calculus:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
