\begin_layout Section
Dissipative parameters
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to explain the terminology, the following list is useful.
 There are some differences that depend on whether one uses sparse matrices
 or functional operators to describe the quantum operators.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
operator: If 
\emph on
sparse=0
\emph default
, an operator is a function with inputs of the mode index (or indices),
 and the wave-function 
\begin_inset Formula $psi$
\end_inset

.
 Operators acting on multiple modes may have two or more indices.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{k}$
\end_inset

 returns a wave-function 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{O}_{k}\left|\psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
sparse_operator: When 
\emph on
sparse=1
\emph default
, operators are sparse matrices.
 This is faster, but uses more memory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Hamiltonian: the function 
\begin_inset Formula $H(psi,p)$
\end_inset

 returns a wave-function 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{H}\left|\psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, if 
\emph on
sparse=0
\emph default
.
 Otherwise, if 
\emph on
sparse=1
\emph default
, it is an operator function 
\begin_inset Formula $H(p)$
\end_inset

 that returns a sparse matrix.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
L{n}: this is a cell array of dissipative or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Lindblad
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 functions.
 The first argument is the mode index, 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, or a vector of two indices, 
\begin_inset Formula $[k_{1},k_{2}]$
\end_inset

, and the last argument p includes parameters.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Description
@(k,p) is used for sparse operators.
 The function returns a sparse matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
@(k,psi,p) is used for operator functions.
 The function can return both 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}_{k}\left|\psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}_{k}^{\dagger}\hat{L}_{k}\left|\psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, as required.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Description
gamma{n}(p): This is a cell array of functions for every type of damping
 process.
 Cell array indices give different types of damping.
 If used, it returns a vector or matrix of damping rates for each type of
 Lindblad operator.
 If omitted, the rates must be included in the operators.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
alpha{n}(k): This is a cell array of noise amplitude vectors or matrices
 for each type of damping process with real noises.
 If 
\series bold
alpha
\series default
 is zero, which is the default, a complex noise is used.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Operators may have one or two mode indices.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Functional operators are slower than sparse operators for small Hilbert
 spaces.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Only the required index combinations are accessed by the Lindblad functions,
 reducing storage.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A separate 
\emph on
gamma
\emph default
 array is more efficient if some Lindblad indices have a zero rate.
\end_layout

