\begin_layout Standard
These correspond to normalized and un-normalized wave-functions.
 The equation can be solved by any 
\begin_inset Formula $method$
\end_inset

 for a Stratonovich SDE.
 For SSE, typically the lowest errors are obtained using an RK4 Schrödinger
 method with projective normalization, @RK4S.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Solving with the MCWF method 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Solving-with-MCWF-1"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At each time step in the numerical simulation with the MCWF method, the
 jump probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta P$
\end_inset

 is first calculated.
 This is carried out by computing the jump probability per unit time of
 each jump operator 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{m}$
\end_inset

 in the master equation, which is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta P_{m}=2\gamma_{m}\langle\psi(t)|L_{m}^{\dagger}L_{m}|\psi(t)\rangle\,.\label{eq:individual_jump_prob-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The calculated jump rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta P_{m}$
\end_inset

 is then compared with a uniform, randomly generated number 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{m}$
\end_inset

 between zero and 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\Delta t$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta P_{m}>r_{m}$
\end_inset

, the state then undergoes the given jump.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

, a jump in any given step become increasingly rare.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After this, the state vector evolves according to the non-hermitian Hamiltonian
 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{eff}$
\end_inset

 in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:non-Hermitian_Hamiltonian"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) as follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{d}{dt}|\psi(t)\rangle=-iH_{eff}|\psi(t)\rangle\label{eq:ODE-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This differential equation is solved by a RK4S algorithm, or others that
 are available.
 These steps are repeated till the final time step, and they constitute
 a single trajectory.
 Many trajectories are taken to compute the expectation values for the observabl
es of interest.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For error-checking, fine step results are checked against a coarse step
 with a noise given by 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{c}=\min\left(r_{1},r_{2}\right)$
\end_inset

, so that the coarse jump occurs if a jump takes place in either fine step.
 This allows errors due to step-size to be accurately estimated by comparing
 the fine and coarse step-size results, just as with continuous noise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The MCWF algorithm described above is carried out simply by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $p.jump=1$
\end_inset

.
 No further inputs from the user are required.
 All other parameters are input exactly the same way as in the SSE numerical
 simulation.
\end_layout

